-android-379594 |title=Man Of Steel official game now available for iPhone, iPad, Android |last=Bhatia |first=Gurman |publisher=[[NDTV]] |date=June 14, 2013 |access-date=March 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809042222/http://gadgets.ndtv.com/games/news/man-of-steel-official-game-now-available-for-iphone-ipad-android-379594 |archive-date=August 9, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MoSVG2\">{{cite web |url=http://appadvice.com/appnn/2013/04/unlock-the-man-of-steels-superpowers-with-this-new-app-from-kelloggs |title=Unlock The Man Of Steel's Superpowers With This New App From Kellogg's |last=Calimlim |first=Aldrin |date=April 19, 2013 |accessdate=March 29, 2018 |website=Appadvice.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809131632/https://appadvice.com/appnn/2013/04/unlock-the-man-of-steels-superpowers-with-this-new-app-from-kelloggs |archive-date=August 9, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BvSVG\">{{cite web |url=http://whowillwingame.batmanvsuperman.com |title=Batman Vs Superman : Who Will Win \u2013 Official Movie Game |website=Batmanvsuperman.com |publisher=[[Warner Bros.]] |access-date=March 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119042725/http://whowillwingame.batmanvsuperman.com/ |archive-date=November 19, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SSVG\">{{cite web |url=http://specialops.suicidesquad.com/ |title=Suicide Squad: Special Ops \u2013 Official Film Game \u2013 August 5, 2016 |publisher=[[Warner Bros.]] |access-date=March 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114083358/http://specialops.suicidesquad.com/ |archive-date=November 14, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"WWVG\">{{cite web |url=https://riseofthewarrior.wonderwomanfilm.com/ |title=Wonder Woman: Rise of the Warrior \u2013 Official Film Game \u2013 August 5, 2016 |publisher=[[Warner Bros.]] |accessdate=March 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112185705/http://riseofthewarrior.wonderwomanfilm.com/ |archive-date=November 12, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"JLVR\">{{cite web |url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/752750/Justice_League_VR_The_Complete_Experience/ |title=Justice League VR: The Complete Experience |website=[[Steam (service)|Steam]] |publisher=[[Warner Bros.]] |access-date=April 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414015428/https://store.steampowered.com/app/752750/Justice_League_VR_The_Complete_Experience/ |archive-date=April 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links| wikt=no | commons=Category:DC Extended Universe | b=no | n=no | q=no | s=no | v=no | voy=no | species=no | d=Q18281265 }}\n* {{Facebook|DCFilmsOfficial|DC Films}}\n* {{Plain link|https://www.dccomics.com/movies|DC Comics Movies}}\n* {{Plain link|http://dcextendeduniverse.wikia.com/wiki/|DC Extended Universe Wiki}}\n\n{{DC Extended Universe|state=expanded}}\n{{DC Comics films}}\n\n[[Category:DC Extended Universe]]\n[[Category:Fictional universes]]\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 2013]]\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DC_Extended_Universe"}
{"title_page": "John Huntington", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|American industrialist and philanthropist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = John Huntington\n| image = <!-- John Huntington 1928.183 o10.jpg -->\n| image_size =\n| caption = Portrait of Huntington drawn {{circa|1917}}\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth-date|March 8, 1832}}\n| birth_place = [[Preston, Lancashire]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|January 10, 1893|March 8, 1832}}\n| death_place = London, England\n| burial_place = [[Lake View Cemetery]]\n| nationality = American\n| occupation = Industrialist, philanthropist\n}}\n\n'''John P. Huntington''' (March 8, 1832 \u2013 January 10, 1893) was an American industrialist and philanthropist. Associated with [[John D. Rockefeller]]'s [[Standard Oil]], he was prominent in the business affairs of [[Cleveland]]'s oil industry. Among other philanthropic activities, funds which he left in a bequest were combined with those of [[Hinman Hurlbut]] and [[Horace Kelley]] to establish the [[Cleveland Museum of Art]] in 1913.\n\n==Biography==\nHuntington was born in [[Preston, Lancashire]], England on March 8, 1832. His father, Hugh Huntington, was a professor of mathematics who founded a school in Preston.<ref name=\"Orth\">{{cite book |last1=Orth |first1=Samuel Peter |title=A History of Cleveland, Ohio: Biographical |date=1910 |pages=368, 371 |publisher=[[S. J. Clarke Publishing Company]] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H5U6AQAAIAAJ |accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref> John, with his wife Jane Beck whom he married in 1852, immigrated to [[Cleveland]], Ohio, in 1854 and worked as a contractor in [[slate roof]]ing. He was employed at Clark, Payne & Co., an [[oil refining]] firm, in 1863, until its [[takeover]] by [[Standard Oil]] in 1870. Other business endeavors included gaining partial ownership of a fleet of lake ships in 1886 and becoming vice-president of the Cleveland Stone Company. He also filed many patents for improvements to [[furnace]]s, oil refinery, and machinery for producing [[oil barrel]]s.<ref name=\"beltmag\">{{cite web|url=https://beltmag.com/rise-cleveland-museum-art/|title=The Rise of the Cleveland Museum of Art|last=Volpe|first=Andrea|date=November 3, 2014|website=[[Belt Magazine]]|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Orth\" /><ref name=\"Rose\">{{cite book|last1=Rose|first1=William Ganson|title=Cleveland: The Making of a City|date=1990|publisher=Kent State University Press|page=491|isbn=0873384288|oclc=932849693|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IT1NVT1vEwUC}}</ref><ref name=\"ECH\">{{cite web|url=https://case.edu/ech/articles/h/huntington-john|title=Huntington, John|date=May 11, 2018|website=Encyclopedia of Cleveland History |publisher=[[Case Western Reserve University]] |access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn active participant in the municipal affairs of Cleveland, Huntington served as a member of the [[Cleveland City Council]] for 13 years (beginning in 1862). In his tenure as a city councilman, he supported the creation of a paid [[fire department]] and a city [[sewer system]], the [[dredging|deepening]] of the [[Cuyahoga River]] [[Channel (geography)|channel]], and the construction of the Superior Viaduct (which closed in 1920, following the opening of the [[Detroit\u2013Superior Bridge]]).<ref name=\"Orth\" /><ref name=\"ECH\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Superior Viaduct |url=https://case.edu/ech/articles/s/superior-viaduct |website=Encyclopedia of Cleveland History |publisher=Case Western Reserve University |accessdate=February 2, 2020  |date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Founders plaque - Ames Atrium - Cleveland Museum of Art (30140588193).jpg|thumb|right|The Cleveland Museum of Art displays its founders names on a plaque in the Ames Family Atrium]]\nHuntington was also a hobby [[philatelist]]. After his tour of Europe and marriage to Mariette L. Goodwin (following his first wife's death in 1882), he turned his interests towards collecting art.<ref name=\"ECH\" /><ref>{{cite book |author1=Holly Rarick Witchey |author2=John Vacha |title=Fine arts in Cleveland : an illustrated history |date=1994 |publisher=[[Indiana University Press]] |isbn=9780253310668 |page=35 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jZXWAAAAMAAJ |accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref> He formed the John Huntington Benevolent Trust on his fifty-seventh birthday in 1889. The fund was mostly based on 500 shares of his Standard Oil stock, and it provided charity to more than 40 cultural and educational institutions.<ref name=\"Orth\" /><ref name=\"Rose\" /><ref name=\"Leedy\">{{cite book |last1=Leedy |first1=Walter C. |editor1-last=Zuppan |editor1-first=Jo |editor2-last=Feingold |editor2-first=Rachel G. |title=Cleveland builds an art museum: patronage, politics, and architecture, 1884-1916 |date=1991 |publisher=Cleveland Museum of Art |isbn=0940717093 |page=12}}</ref> \n\nIn his [[Will and testament|will]] written in 1889, Huntington established the John Huntington Art and Polytechnic Trust with the goal of producing a \"gallery and museum\" and a \"free evening polytechnic school\". The trustee of his estate, Henry Clay Ranney, was also the trustee for the estates of [[Hinman Hurlbut]] and [[Horace Kelley]]; Ranney channeled the bequests from all three estates toward the establishment of the [[Cleveland Museum of Art]].<ref name=\"CMA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.clevelandart.org/research/in-the-library/collection-in-focus/cleveland-museum-art-founders|title=Cleveland Museum of Art: Founders|date=October 22, 2012|website=[[Cleveland Museum of Art]]|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Leedy\" /> Huntington was also a member of several [[fraternal order]]s; he received the 32nd Degree from the [[Scottish Rite]], and was affiliated with the [[Independent Order of Odd Fellows]] and the [[Knights of Pythias]].<ref name=\"Wright\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Wright |editor1-first=George Frederick |editor1-link=George Frederick Wright |title=A Standard History of Lorain County, Ohio |volume=2 |date=1916 |publisher=[[Lewis Publishing Company]] |page=947 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fz8VAAAAYAAJ |accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith Jane Beck, Huntington raised five children to adulthood, including his son W.R. Huntington who later became a prominent industrialist of the [[Lorain County, Ohio|Lorain County]] area. John Huntington, along with his family, were members of the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]].<ref name=\"Wright\" /> He also owned a [[hobby farm]] on [[Lake Erie]] on which he built many structures including a house, a [[steam pump]] [[irrigation]] system, and a [[water tower]]. After his death in 1893, the [[Cleveland Metroparks|Cleveland Metropolitan Park System]] purchased the lakefront property and named it the Huntington Reservation in his honor. He is buried at [[Lake View Cemetery]] in Cleveland.<ref name=\"ECH\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://clevelandhistorical.org/index.php/items/show/244|title=Huntington Reservation|website=Cleveland Historical|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=State History Publications, LLC |title=Ohio historic places dictionary. |volume=2 |date=2008 |publisher=North American Book Dist LLC |isbn=9781878592705 |page=236}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huntington, John}}\n[[Category:1832 births]]\n[[Category:1893 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Freemasons]]\n[[Category:American industrialists]]\n[[Category:American Odd Fellows]]\n[[Category:Burials at Lake View Cemetery, Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Cleveland City Council members]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Preston, Lancashire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|American industrialist and philanthropist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = John Huntington\n| image = <!-- John Huntington 1928.183 o10.jpg -->\n| image_size =\n| caption = Portrait of Huntington drawn {{circa|1917}}\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth-date|March 8, 1832}}\n| birth_place = [[Preston, Lancashire]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|January 10, 1893|March 8, 1832}}\n| death_place = London, England\n| burial_place = [[Lake View Cemetery]]\n| nationality = American\n| occupation = [[Industrialist]], [[philanthropist]]\n}}\n\n'''John P. Huntington''' (March 8, 1832 \u2013 January 10, 1893) was an American industrialist and philanthropist. Associated with [[John D. Rockefeller]]'s [[Standard Oil]], he was prominent in the business affairs of [[Cleveland]]'s oil industry. Among other philanthropic activities, funds which he left in a bequest were combined with those of [[Hinman Hurlbut]] and [[Horace Kelley]] to establish the [[Cleveland Museum of Art]] in 1913.\n\n==Biography==\nHuntington was born in [[Preston, Lancashire]], England on March 8, 1832. His father, Hugh Huntington, was a professor of mathematics who founded a school in Preston.<ref name=\"Orth\">{{cite book |last1=Orth |first1=Samuel Peter |title=A History of Cleveland, Ohio: Biographical |date=1910 |pages=368, 371 |publisher=[[S. J. Clarke Publishing Company]] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H5U6AQAAIAAJ |accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref> John, with his wife Jane Beck whom he married in 1852, immigrated to [[Cleveland]], Ohio, in 1854 and worked as a contractor in [[slate roof]]ing. He was employed at Clark, Payne & Co., an [[oil refining]] firm, in 1863, until its [[takeover]] by [[Standard Oil]] in 1870. Other business endeavors included gaining partial ownership of a fleet of lake ships in 1886 and becoming [[vice president]] of the Cleveland Stone Company. He also filed many patents for improvements to [[furnace]]s, oil refinery, and machinery for producing [[oil barrel]]s.<ref name=\"beltmag\">{{cite web|url=https://beltmag.com/rise-cleveland-museum-art/|title=The Rise of the Cleveland Museum of Art|last=Volpe|first=Andrea|date=November 3, 2014|website=[[Belt Magazine]]|language=en-US|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Orth\" /><ref name=\"Rose\">{{cite book|last1=Rose|first1=William Ganson|title=Cleveland: The Making of a City|date=1990|publisher=Kent State University Press|page=491|isbn=0873384288|oclc=932849693|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IT1NVT1vEwUC}}</ref><ref name=\"ECH\">{{cite web|url=https://case.edu/ech/articles/h/huntington-john|title=Huntington, John|date=May 11, 2018|website=Encyclopedia of Cleveland History |publisher=[[Case Western Reserve University]] |language=en|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn active participant in the municipal affairs of Cleveland, Huntington served as a member of the [[Cleveland City Council]] for 13 years (beginning in 1862). In his tenure as a city councilman, he supported the creation of a paid [[fire department]] and a city [[sewer system]], the [[dredging|deepening]] of the [[Cuyahoga River]] [[Channel (geography)|channel]], and the construction of the Superior Viaduct (which closed in 1920, following the opening of the [[Detroit\u2013Superior Bridge]]).<ref name=\"Orth\" /><ref name=\"ECH\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Superior Viaduct |url=https://case.edu/ech/articles/s/superior-viaduct |website=Encyclopedia of Cleveland History |publisher=Case Western Reserve University |accessdate=February 2, 2020 |language=en |date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Founders plaque - Ames Atrium - Cleveland Museum of Art (30140588193).jpg|thumb|right|The Cleveland Museum of Art displays its founders names on a plaque in the Ames Family Atrium]]\nHuntington was also a hobby [[philatelist]]. After his tour of [[Europe]] and marriage to Mariette L. Goodwin (following his first wife's death in 1882), he turned his interests towards collecting art.<ref name=\"ECH\" /><ref>{{cite book |author1=Holly Rarick Witchey |author2=John Vacha |title=Fine arts in Cleveland : an illustrated history |date=1994 |publisher=[[Indiana University Press]] |isbn=9780253310668 |page=35 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jZXWAAAAMAAJ |accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref> He formed the John Huntington Benevolent Trust on his fifty-seventh birthday in 1889. The fund was mostly based on 500 shares of his Standard Oil stock, and it provided charity to more than 40 cultural and educational institutions.<ref name=\"Orth\" /><ref name=\"Rose\" /><ref name=\"Leedy\">{{cite book |last1=Leedy |first1=Walter C. |editor1-last=Zuppan |editor1-first=Jo |editor2-last=Feingold |editor2-first=Rachel G. |title=Cleveland builds an art museum: patronage, politics, and architecture, 1884-1916 |date=1991 |publisher=Cleveland Museum of Art |isbn=0940717093 |page=12}}</ref> \n\nIn his [[Will and testament|will]] written in 1889, Huntington established the John Huntington Art and Polytechnic Trust with the goal of producing a \"gallery and museum\" and a \"free evening polytechnic school\". The trustee of his estate, Henry Clay Ranney, was also the trustee for the estates of [[Hinman Hurlbut]] and [[Horace Kelley]]; Ranney channeled the bequests from all three estates toward the establishment of the [[Cleveland Museum of Art]].<ref name=\"CMA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.clevelandart.org/research/in-the-library/collection-in-focus/cleveland-museum-art-founders|title=Cleveland Museum of Art: Founders|date=October 22, 2012|website=[[Cleveland Museum of Art]]|language=en|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Leedy\" /> Huntington was also a member of several [[fraternal order]]s; he received the 32nd Degree from the [[Scottish Rite]], and was affiliated with the [[Independent Order of Odd Fellows]] and the [[Knights of Pythias]].<ref name=\"Wright\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Wright |editor1-first=George Frederick |editor1-link=George Frederick Wright |title=A Standard History of Lorain County, Ohio |volume=2 |date=1916 |publisher=[[Lewis Publishing Company]] |page=947 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fz8VAAAAYAAJ |accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith Jane Beck, Huntington raised five children to adulthood, including his son W.R. Huntington who later became a prominent industrialist of the [[Lorain County, Ohio|Lorain County]] area. John Huntington, along with his family, were members of the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]].<ref name=\"Wright\" /> He also owned a [[hobby farm]] on [[Lake Erie]] on which he built many structures including a house, a [[steam pump]] [[irrigation]] system, and a [[water tower]]. After his death in 1893, the [[Cleveland Metroparks|Cleveland Metropolitan Park System]] purchased the lakefront property and named it the Huntington Reservation in his honor. He is buried at [[Lake View Cemetery]] in Cleveland.<ref name=\"ECH\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://clevelandhistorical.org/index.php/items/show/244|title=Huntington Reservation|website=Cleveland Historical|language=en|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=State History Publications, LLC |title=Ohio historic places dictionary. |volume=2 |date=2008 |publisher=North American Book Dist LLC |isbn=9781878592705 |page=236}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huntington, John}}\n[[Category:1832 births]]\n[[Category:1893 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Freemasons]]\n[[Category:American industrialists]]\n[[Category:American Odd Fellows]]\n[[Category:Burials at Lake View Cemetery, Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Cleveland City Council members]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Preston, Lancashire]]\n", "name_user": "Aranya", "label": "safe", "comment": "delink and simplify refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Huntington"}
